# Patella

> The patella is the **largest sesamoid bone in the body**, embedded within the quadriceps tendon. It increases the mechanical advantage of knee extension by ~50%.

## 🔗 Connected Structures
- [[Femur]] — **Patellofemoral joint** — glides along the femoral trochlear groove
- [[Tibia]] — Indirectly via the **patellar tendon** to the tibial tuberosity

## 🔗 Associated Muscles
- [[Quadriceps Femoris]] — Inserts via quadriceps tendon onto the patella base; patellar tendon continues to tibial tuberosity

## 🗂️ Structure

| Part | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Base | Superior; quadriceps tendon attachment |
| Apex | Inferior; patellar tendon origin |
| Anterior surface | Rough; subcutaneous |
| Articular surface | Medial + lateral facets (contact femoral trochlea) |

## 🔑 Functions
1. **Increases mechanical advantage** — extends the lever arm of the quadriceps by ~50%
2. **Reduces friction** — protects quadriceps tendon from bone contact
3. **Protects the anterior knee joint**

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Patellar fracture** — Direct blow or forced quadriceps contraction
- **Patellofemoral pain syndrome (Runner's knee)** — Anterior knee pain; common in young women and athletes
- **Patellar dislocation** — Lateral dislocation most common; increased Q-angle is a risk factor
- **Patellar tendinopathy (Jumper's knee)** — Repetitive jumping sports
- **Osgood-Schlatter disease** — Tibial tuberosity apophysitis in adolescents


